data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure, shows both values instead of just "expected true, got false"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `Contains(collection, element)`
  - `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
  - `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- **Add message parameters** — when `Assert.IsTrue` is unavoidable, include a message string for diagnostics

**Avoid:** `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` → use `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` instead.

If you want even richer fluent assertions, the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package is popular:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
